<h1>@HI{{te mo}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vte{{}} <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong>, ...
<li> @Aistem{{}}@HI{{kute}} <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong>, ...
<li> @Anastem{{}}@HI{{de}} <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong>, ...
<li> @N{{}}@HI{{de}} <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong>, ...
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
This expression is used to mean "even if" or "even though" the conditon in the subordinate clause is true,
the action expressed in the main clause will take place. The subordinate clause is not what would be
expected from the main clause.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{ikura}} can be placed before the subordinate clause to indicate that a condition is about to be presented.
@HI{{ikura}} stresses the degree of conditionality.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{rain}}ga @KJ{{descend}}ttemo, @KJ{{wash^laundry}}shimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Even if it rains I'll do the laundry.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{day^weekday^day}}demo, @KJ{{work}}kimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Even if it is Sunday I will work.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{what}}wo @KJ{{eat}}betemo, oishii desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No matter what I eat it tastes good.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ikura @KJ{{tall}}kutemo, @KJ{{buy}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No matter how expensive it is I will buy it.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{te mo ii desuka}} is an idiomatic expression used to request permission to do something.
</p>

<p>
With a WH word @HI{{te mo}} means "no matter WH".
</p>

